By my count they've already launched 2 since July 14 2017:  1-Nov 29th. 
They launched 4 other ballistic missiles: 1 - July 28th; 3 - Aug 26th; 1 - Aug 29th; 1 Sep 15th;
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_North_Korean_missile_tests These are land based. I guess I have some questions about what is defined as a ICBM. If the missile fails the 5,500 km range test but was intended to be over (hard for us to know) is it an ICBM or SRBM? I'm going to qualify ICBM as clearly demonstrating the ability to clear the 5,500 km range.  They've launched 3 total and only got ICBM level since July 2017 (some reports say April?).  Hard to get any info on budget or supply chain - that is most likely only information that the IC has. North Korea runs on a matched FY with calendar year so I expect a new budget to exist for 2018 - likely already allocated but probably spurred on with the success of the Nov 29th launch. If that launched 3 in 2017, 3 more in 2018 is very probable. The constraining factors would be supplies, build time (and pipeline), and political timing - all of which I have no idea about. From a bottom up perspective, they have a few items to demonstrate. ICBM from SLBM - which doesn't qualify for this count. Solid state fuel (which will give them a huge edge). Given the steps to getting there is shooting off a bunch of ICBMs, then I think we'll see a lot of launches.
